    {
      "title": "Nominal Sentences (المبتدأ والخبر)",
      "titleArabic": "المبتدأ والخبر",
      "content": [
        "Nominal sentences consist of mubtada' (subject) and khabar (predicate). Understanding their types, word order, and when either can be omitted is essential for Arabic syntax."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Mubtada' must be definite (with few exceptions)",
        "Khabar can be a word, phrase, or sentence",
        "Word order can be reversed for emphasis or necessity",
        "Agreement in number and gender is required"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "الْكِتَابُ جَدِيدٌ", "english": "The book is new" },
        { "arabic": "الطُّلَّابُ فِي الْفَصْلِ", "english": "The students are in the classroom" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Assimilated Verbs (الفعل المثال)",
      "titleArabic": "الفعل المثال",
      "content": [
        "Assimilated verbs have wāw or yā' as their first radical. The weak letter often drops in the present tense and imperative forms."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "First radical is wāw (most common) or yā'",
        "Wāw usually drops in present tense: وَجَدَ → يَجِدُ",
        "Pattern in māḍī remains regular",
        "Common verbs: وَجَدَ, وَصَلَ, وَعَدَ, وَضَعَ, وَقَفَ"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "وَجَدَ - يَجِدُ", "english": "to find (wāw drops)" },
        { "arabic": "وَصَلَ - يَصِلُ", "english": "to arrive (wāw drops)" },
        { "arabic": "وَعَدَ - يَعِدُ", "english": "to promise (wāw drops)" }
      ]
    }
  ],
